'''Franklin D'Olier "F.D." Reeve''' (September 18, 1928 - June 28, 2013<ref name=times>[http://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/08/books/f-d-reeve-poet-and-translator-dies-at-84.html?_r=0 ''New York Times'' F.D. Reeve, poet and translator dies at 84]</ref>) was an American academic, writer, poet, [[Russian language|Russian]] translator, and editor.<ref>[http://www.nyqpoets.net/bio1.php?pid=390 NYQ Poets - bio1]</ref> He was also the father of "[[Superman (1978 film)|Superman]]" actor [[Christopher Reeve]].<ref>[http://www.filmreference.com/film/77/Christopher-Reeve.html Christopher Reeve biography at FilmReference.com]</ref> He was the grandson of the first [[American Legion]] national commander, [[Franklin D'Olier]].

==Life and career==
Reeve was born in Philadelphia, the son of Anne Conrad D'Olier and Richard Henry Reeve.<ref>[http://www.wargs.com/other/reeve.html Ancestry of Christopher Reeve]</ref> He was brought up outside New York City. Reeve worked in the wheat fields for a while during college and, after graduation, was a Hudson River longshoreman for a while.  He graduated from [[Princeton University]] (1950) and [[Columbia University]] (1958), and in 1961 was one of the first exchanges between the American Council of Learned Societies and the USSR Academy of Sciences. In the late summer of 1962 he accompanied [[Robert Frost]] to [[Russia]] for his meeting with [[Nikita Khrushchev]], where Reeve served as Frost's translator.

Reeve started his academic career teaching Russian language and literature at [[Columbia University]].  After teaching at Columbia, Reeve moved to [[Wesleyan University]] in 1962 as chairman of the Russian Department.  In 1967, he joined Wesleyan's inter-disciplinary College of Letters where he taught literature, humanities and creative writing until his retirement in 2002.  During the course of his career he had visiting appointments at [[Oxford University]], [[Yale University|Yale]], and Columbia.<ref>[http://www.albany.edu/writers-inst/webpages4/archives/fdreeve_bluecat08.html F. D. Reeve and The Three Blue Cats jazz band]</ref>

Since 1994 he lived in [[Wilmington, Vermont]] with his wife the novelist Laura Stevenson.  Reeve was an officer of the [[Poetry Society of America]], the founding editor of ''"Poetry Review,"'' the secretary of [[Poets House]] in its formative years, and was associated with the New England Poetry Club and the [[New York Quarterly]].  He published over two dozen books of poetry, fiction, criticism, and translation.

Reeve died on June 28, 2013 at Dartmouth Hitchcock Hospital in [[Lebanon, New Hampshire]] from complications from [[diabetes]]. He was 84 and is survived by his fourth wife, Laura C. Stevenson, a novelist: his son Benjamin; a daughter, Alya, and two sons, Brock and Mark, all from his second marriage; two stepdaughters, Katharine O’Connell and Margaret Staloff; his sister, Anne Reeve Childs; his brother, Richard; and 18 grandchildren.<ref name=times/>

